commit_message:
Call _init_volume_driver in backup manager

When fixing backup using temp snapshot code path, the call to
_init_volume_driver was missed:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/321943/

For drivers that rely on do_setup to initialize the driver, this
is a problem because the driver cannot be used without this call.

This patch fixes the problem by calling _init_volume_driver in
init_host.

Change-Id: Ic197046a480dbf8d73a229580e59cd6d489355fa
Closes-Bug: #1594225
(cherry picked from commit cbdd0fa1fab24bbb891044b1e4aa56859cab75c4)

subject: devstack: disable workload_partition for compute polling
revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2016-06-30 07:08:15.000000000', 'files': ['devstack/plugin.sh'], 'message': 'devstack: disable workload_partition for compute polling

I7adef87b03129f4f8b38109bf547c7403cc6adad introduces a very good
feature to partition workload for central polling agent, but it
seems not so much value for compute polling agent, which is
natrually workload distributed. There are efforts to reduce the
load of nova-api by adding instance cache in compute polling
agent side, if we increase the compute polling process in the
same node, pollsters may be a bit quicker than before, but things
will get worse for nova-api. And if we want to accelerate the
pollsters, we can search for a better solution instead of increasing
state shared workers.

For most case, I cannot see there is a need to partition workload
on a single node, especially when we running a devstack.

This patch removes the workload_partition setting in devstack
installation for compute polling agent even when there is a
coordinate backend configured. If an user does want this, he can
edit the /etc/ceilometer/ceilometer.conf and restart the compute
polling agent in screen -x, as the usual way.

Change-Id: If4dbcf1d02f5f8bdc189b272fb350a800e23d760
'}]
commit_message:
devstack: disable workload_partition for compute polling

I7adef87b03129f4f8b38109bf547c7403cc6adad introduces a very good
feature to partition workload for central polling agent, but it
seems not so much value for compute polling agent, which is
natrually workload distributed. There are efforts to reduce the
load of nova-api by adding instance cache in compute polling
agent side, if we increase the compute polling process in the
same node, pollsters may be a bit quicker than before, but things
will get worse for nova-api. And if we want to accelerate the
pollsters, we can search for a better solution instead of increasing
state shared workers.

For most case, I cannot see there is a need to partition workload
on a single node, especially when we running a devstack.

This patch removes the workload_partition setting in devstack
installation for compute polling agent even when there is a
coordinate backend configured. If an user does want this, he can
edit the /etc/ceilometer/ceilometer.conf and restart the compute
polling agent in screen -x, as the usual way.

Change-Id: If4dbcf1d02f5f8bdc189b272fb350a800e23d760

commit_message:
Declare supports_device_tagging in all drivers

When the libvirt driver support for device tagging was merged, the
supports_device_tagging capability was added to the libvirt driver and
the base virt driver. However, other virt drivers that don't yet
support tagging were not updated with the new capability. This patch
fixes this.

Change-Id: Ic5c35661981824e047b0ccc97442fb4b538c677c

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 782, 'name': 'John Garbutt', 'email': 'john.garbutt@stackhpc.com', 'username': 'johngarbutt'}, {'_account_id': 5170, 'name': 'Microsoft Hyper-V CI', 'email': 'hyper-v_ci@microsoft.com', 'username': 'hyper-v-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 6062, 'name': 'jichenjc', 'email': 'jichenjc@cn.ibm.com', 'username': 'jichenjc'}, {'_account_id': 6167, 'name': "Ken'ichi Ohmichi", 'email': 'ken1ohmichi@gmail.com', 'username': 'oomichi'}, {'_account_id': 6873, 'name': 'Matt Riedemann', 'email': 'mriedem.os@gmail.com', 'username': 'mriedem'}, {'_account_id': 8556, 'name': 'Ghanshyam', 'display_name': 'Ghanshyam Maan', 'email': 'gmaan@ghanshyammann.com', 'username': 'ghanshyam'}, {'_account_id': 9578, 'name': 'DB Datasets CI', 'email': 'turbo-hipster@lists.rcbops.com', 'username': 'turbo-hipster', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 10118, 'name': 'IBM PowerKVM CI', 'email': 'kvmpower@linux.vnet.ibm.com', 'username': 'powerkvm', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 10385, 'name': 'Citrix XenServer CI', 'username': 'citrix_xenserver_ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 15286, 'name': 'XenProject CI', 'email': 'openstack-ci@xenproject.org', 'username': 'XenProject-CI', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 16376, 'name': 'Intel NFV CI', 'email': 'openstack-nfv-ci@intel.com', 'username': 'intel-nfv-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-06-29 08:07:21.000000000', 'files': ['api-ref/source/parameters.yaml', 'nova/compute/api.py'], 'message': 'Return snapshot_id in os-assisted-volume-snapshots POST

os-assisted-volume-snapshots POST API is used to create
snapshot of volumes on backends such as NFS or GlusterFS
by storing data as qcow2 files on these volumes.

NOTE- This API is only used by Cinder.

This API's request accept "snapshot_id" and optional "id"
in create_info object.
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/compute/schemas/assisted_volume_snapshots.py#L27-L36

and return "id" in response which is nothing but the "id" sent
in create_info during request.
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/api.py#L3453

But this returned "id" seems meaningless as this is/can not be used anywhere.
 - Delete operation requires "snapshot_id" (which can be different than "id").
 - Cinder store the snapshot info with "snapshot_id" not with "id" sent during
   create_info in POST API.

This seems like just return back the input id which is not being
considered anywhere.

So if anyone create snapshot via this API and use returned "id" for
delete or any other operation then, it is going to be wrong input id.
And end up with obsolete status on Cinder side:
 - delete operation is done using qcow2 file name not by input id. So no issue.
 - But during delete operation, libvirt driver try to update snapshot
   status in cinder which will throw exception as it would not find the
   snapshot (in this case, Nova just log the exception).

As of now, it does not create any issue on Cinder side as "id" is not
being passed/used there.

Second issue is if "id" is not being passed in request then POST API's respone
will have "id" as None which does not seems good response.

It make sense if POST API return the create_info["snapshot_id"]
instead of create_info["id"] which can be used meaningfully.

NOTE- There is no change is API response fields, it change the
value returned in attribute "id".

Change-Id: Ibd76b31b79461db2313d0fca269c685fcee9448b
'}]
commit_message:
Return snapshot_id in os-assisted-volume-snapshots POST

os-assisted-volume-snapshots POST API is used to create
snapshot of volumes on backends such as NFS or GlusterFS
by storing data as qcow2 files on these volumes.

NOTE- This API is only used by Cinder.

This API's request accept "snapshot_id" and optional "id"
in create_info object.
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/compute/schemas/assisted_volume_snapshots.py#L27-L36

and return "id" in response which is nothing but the "id" sent
in create_info during request.
https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/api.py#L3453

But this returned "id" seems meaningless as this is/can not be used anywhere.
 - Delete operation requires "snapshot_id" (which can be different than "id").
 - Cinder store the snapshot info with "snapshot_id" not with "id" sent during
   create_info in POST API.

This seems like just return back the input id which is not being
considered anywhere.

So if anyone create snapshot via this API and use returned "id" for
delete or any other operation then, it is going to be wrong input id.
And end up with obsolete status on Cinder side:
 - delete operation is done using qcow2 file name not by input id. So no issue.
 - But during delete operation, libvirt driver try to update snapshot
   status in cinder which will throw exception as it would not find the
   snapshot (in this case, Nova just log the exception).

As of now, it does not create any issue on Cinder side as "id" is not
being passed/used there.

Second issue is if "id" is not being passed in request then POST API's respone
will have "id" as None which does not seems good response.

It make sense if POST API return the create_info["snapshot_id"]
instead of create_info["id"] which can be used meaningfully.

NOTE- There is no change is API response fields, it change the
value returned in attribute "id".

Change-Id: Ibd76b31b79461db2313d0fca269c685fcee9448b

commit_message:
Fix doc publishing for infra

Documents that we only publish in the release pipeline, need to get
published to the top level directory as well as to a versioned subdir.

Create docs-tags job for publishing of these repositories, like it was
done for normal python projects.

Remove the storyboard publish jobs, we can use the normal infra publish
jobs for these. ci.openstack.org is not used anymore and the location
http://ci.openstack.org/storyboard
redirects to http://docs.openstack.org/infra/storyboard/

Also, update a misleading description.

Change-Id: Ibef97f8d0c06b9f7f000872de14283e2911d3099

Add conditional for overlay network settings

A conditional has been added to the ``_local_ip`` settings used in
the ``neutron_local_ip`` which removes the hard requirement for an
overlay network to be set within a deployment. If no overlay network
is set within the deployment the ``local_ip`` will be set to the
value of ``ansible_ssh_host``.

Manual cherry-pick of I954a46443b5434b589226c4999e71bd6ba6a5c0b

Change-Id: Ia432fd53167a643bf2f1577e4f8b3988e4035cd6

subject: Save Measurements that arrive before their SubAlarms
revisions:
[{'number': 6, 'created': '2016-06-27 14:41:33.000000000', 'files': ['thresh/src/main/java/monasca/thresh/infrastructure/thresholding/MetricAggregationBolt.java', 'thresh/src/test/java/monasca/thresh/infrastructure/thresholding/MetricAggregationBoltTest.java'], 'message': "Save Measurements that arrive before their SubAlarms

Thresh creates an Alarm when a new Measurement matches an
AlarmDefinition. The previous Thresh code just discarded the
Measurement if it arrived before the newly created SubAlarm,
which was likely to occur. This code saves a Measurement that
does not match an existing SubAlarm in the expectation that the
SubAlarm will arrive very soon. It then adds the Measurement
to the SubAlarm. If the measurement would cause the SubAlarm to
transition to the ALARM state, that happens.

This is more important for determinstic alarms because they will get
fewer Measurements and ignoring the first one may prevent an Alarm's
state going to ALARM when it should

Change-Id: I08e9e481ad55862ba602eba5a68eb371b1d35bbc
"}]
commit_message:
Save Measurements that arrive before their SubAlarms

Thresh creates an Alarm when a new Measurement matches an
AlarmDefinition. The previous Thresh code just discarded the
Measurement if it arrived before the newly created SubAlarm,
which was likely to occur. This code saves a Measurement that
does not match an existing SubAlarm in the expectation that the
SubAlarm will arrive very soon. It then adds the Measurement
to the SubAlarm. If the measurement would cause the SubAlarm to
transition to the ALARM state, that happens.

This is more important for determinstic alarms because they will get
fewer Measurements and ignoring the first one may prevent an Alarm's
state going to ALARM when it should

Change-Id: I08e9e481ad55862ba602eba5a68eb371b1d35bbc

1. Added 4 unit tests for migrate_volume() to cover following cases:

2. Added a unit test for create_volume_from_snapshot() to cover:

commit_message:
Implement unit test for HPE Lefthand driver

1. Added 4 unit tests for migrate_volume() to cover following cases:
   * when volume is on different backend
   * when volume is on different management group
   * volume is exported
   * input volume does not exists in management group
2. Added a unit test for create_volume_from_snapshot() to cover:
   * when replication enabled and snapshot is scheduled
   * when replication enable and getSnapshotByName fails with HTTPNotFound
3. Added unit test for create_cloned_volume() to cover:
   * when replication enabled and volume is created on replica node
   * when replication enabled and volume creation fails with HTTPServerError

Change-Id: Iffa4188513082d298d36cd8d298ed9047ca6646a

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-06-17 03:29:42.000000000', 'files': ['tox.ini'], 'message': 'Fix tox lines so test_label may be specified

The test commands hard-coded a "test_label" argument to "manage.py test"
which meant it was not possible to pass one in to limit the test scope.

To do so, you testers will need to specify the testing "project" unlike
the run_tests.sh usage where the project was determined automatically,
for example:

   tox -e py27-horizon horizon.test.tests.utils

Change-Id: Ie7a97a946f81868b6e994084e2fb31dd653dc944
Closes-Bug: 1593537
'}]
commit_message:
Fix tox lines so test_label may be specified

The test commands hard-coded a "test_label" argument to "manage.py test"
which meant it was not possible to pass one in to limit the test scope.

To do so, you testers will need to specify the testing "project" unlike
the run_tests.sh usage where the project was determined automatically,
for example:

   tox -e py27-horizon horizon.test.tests.utils

Change-Id: Ie7a97a946f81868b6e994084e2fb31dd653dc944
Closes-Bug: 1593537

commit_message:
Correct use of isotime

Looking through the uses of utils.isotime, there were several
calls that should have used subsecond=True but were not.

According to the v3 spec, the timestamps in tokens are
"string, ISO 8601 extended format date time with microseconds",
as such, subsecond=True should be used for these timestamps.

Change-Id: I0f1f493404f1e312049c6efbf1ace6c4e23e11ac

commit_message:
Added the ip_vs kernel module to all openstack hosts

The "ip_vs" module is needed in high availability situations where
keepalived is used, specifically Neutron L3HA. Without this module
loaded the neutron l3 agent can crash like so:

    neutron_agents_container-cf16a000/modprobe.log:1:Jun 27 15:09:02
      neutron_agents_container-cf16a000 modprobe: ERROR: could not
      insert 'ip_vs': Operation not permitted ?

Backport-Of: I957462f0adafcbe9655696d8f9aed7252f5c85c3
Change-Id: I8d30d6af8f1bbac994cbcc434f5144a645803acd
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

subject: Attempt to find resource by ID, without kwargs
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-06-29 18:12:06.000000000', 'files': ['osc_lib/utils.py', 'osc_lib/tests/test_utils.py'], 'message': 'Attempt to find resource by ID, without kwargs

In keystone, to look up resources we just need the ID. Supplying
query arguments in a get() request to the client will result in
a list being performed. The resulting query will always come up
with no hits since it'll be trying to find the user "name" even
if an ID is given.

Change-Id: I111b2730eefec83968ee89aa4a56cb518ca9b203
Closes-Bug: #1597246
'}]
commit_message:
Attempt to find resource by ID, without kwargs

In keystone, to look up resources we just need the ID. Supplying
query arguments in a get() request to the client will result in
a list being performed. The resulting query will always come up
with no hits since it'll be trying to find the user "name" even
if an ID is given.

Change-Id: I111b2730eefec83968ee89aa4a56cb518ca9b203

commit_message:
Horizon selects are now themable: Senlin Panels

Based on Diana's work.
Complete for Admin Panels: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/290204/

Horizon used a standard select input. Unfortunately this type of
input is only customizable to a small extend. Note: not all
ChoiceFields were converted because they have unexpected
impact.

Change-Id: Ibbe357123999d2575ebe1eeb5ba202f58ea00a9d
Partially-implements: blueprint horizon-theme-css-reorg

commit_message:
Add strict Boolean checking for qos delete

There is no strict boolean checking for the parameter
"force" of API /qos-specs.
This patch adds a strict checking for it to prevent
invalid value, and adds a test case for this
change as well.

Closes-Bug: #1594261
Change-Id: I59c24454a885310d463690cd08d0b39a0624163e

commit_message:
Adding Host Config doc

Host configurations is used to specify the physical
host type and different configuration for host system.
Used by features like Port binding and Router scheduling.

Updated patch after review.

Change-Id: Ib8d75c328001503dd2f77343e99a83ae26aead9c

commit_message:
on-delete cascade rule for resource_data

During deleting of resource, the resource_data is also loaded in memory
and then deleted. This is not performant. The passive_delete option in
relationship deletes the relation without loading the children. This
patch configures the resource to have a passive-delete relationship with
resource_data and configures ondelete CASCADE so that the DB takes care
of deleting the resource_data when a resource is deleted.

This patch proposes the following changes:
- When deleting a resource do not load resource_data.
- When a resource is deleted, DB takes care of deleting resource_data.

The resource data remains intact when the FK constraints are deleted and
added to reflect on-delete cascade.

Change-Id: I4162e6f9ad9582fcb304887e5d3718de220231ec
Closes-Bug: #1573585

commit_message:
Remove DictCompat from InstanceAction

This change removes NovaObjectDictCompat from the InstanceAction and
InstanceActionEvent objects. Changes were made from dict syntax to use
dot syntax or getattr/setattr. The API tests were also updated to mock
out the compute api instead of the db api. This allowed the mocks to
return objects (as the API would), instead of db model dictionaries.

New private methods were made in the API tests to compare an
action/event with a given request. These were compared prior using key
deletion and dictionary equality. Now, because these are using objects,
it was changed over to new methods, which borrow from o.vo's compare_obj
fixture, which is used to compare objects to a dictionary.

Within fake_server_actions, there were events and actions that were
stored as dictionaries. These were to be returned by the DB, so
dictionaries are still valid for those. An objectified version of those
dictionaries were also added, which are meant to be returned by the
compute API.

The cells' compute InstanceActionAPI also needed to be changed over.
Originally, the api was taking in dicts from RPC and passing them back
from the API. Now, the API is changed to convert the primitives it
receives from the RPC API into objects.

Depends-On: I3e5143bc872ab4cb645d09c7e969fd1cf9c7985c
Change-Id: Id90ae9ca29d484dede90b200c32641c4142f0b13
Partially-Implements: bp rm-object-dict-compat-newton

commit_message:
Remove install test requirements

Because one package with same name in different test-requirements
which are in different project may has different version. The test
dependency packages are not needed on installing process, so I hope
remove this to speed up the installation process.

Change-Id: Id4bc73b5a5839068d3f23e8130ec8bd8cb85bfdf

centos-release-openstack-mitaka 1.3 is now available via the
delorean-mitaka-testing repo. We need to install this directly instead
of the 1.2 version as otherwise the subsequent 'yum update' tries to

"}]
commit_message:
Fix build for oraclelinux base

centos-release-openstack-mitaka 1.3 is now available via the
delorean-mitaka-testing repo. We need to install this directly instead
of the 1.2 version as otherwise the subsequent 'yum update' tries to
install it and fails on the centos-release dependency which is
incompatible with the oraclelinux base.

Closes-Bug: 1576238

Change-Id: I51cb372424b27b32e95f9e81c5dddbe8e49a6131

validate_flavor() use list() to get flavors, then use "for" to find the flavor.
It is slow when nova has many flavors.
The id of flavor and the name of flavor are unique, so we can use get().

Change-Id: Ibbee6b8029b6f3184c58e2d8fc69f864f6796eb0
'}]
commit_message:
validate_flavor should use get() replace list()

validate_flavor() use list() to get flavors, then use "for" to find the flavor.
It is slow when nova has many flavors.
The id of flavor and the name of flavor are unique, so we can use get().

Change-Id: Ibbee6b8029b6f3184c58e2d8fc69f864f6796eb0

need to explicitly do this.

commit_message:
Use elevated context to query DB in VolumeNumberWeigher

Currently tenant would fail to create volume, if cinder uses
VolumeNumberWeigher.

This will elevate tenant to admin privilege, then VolumeNumberWeigher
has the privilege to get volume count of each hosts.

Change-Id: If2da54b650091e1a7016b2049da9e833fada38d7
Closes-Bug: #1594294

commit_message:
Replace HTTP 'magic numbers' with constants

Replace HTTP 'magic numbers' with constants provided by http_client/httplib

commit_message:
Validate discovery url when create a bay

Currently when we create a Bay, magnum is not enough to prevent bay creation failure,
due to Invalid discovery url can be referenced and there're no check toward it. We
should check the discovery url before creating bay, a 400 Invalid will be raised if
the discovery url is invalid:
1.the discovery url should be a correct url of etcd cluster.
2.the discovery url should have suitable cluster size.

Change-Id: Ib75f9f2aade18b16dd46035efe139311faf93e1e

commit_message:
Add whitelist and blacklist file options to tempest run

This commit uses the regex_builder logic from os-testr to construct a
regex given a whitelist and/or a blacklist file. Where all matches from
the blacklist file will be excluded and all matches from the whitelist file
will be included.

Partially-Implements bp tempest-run-cmd

commit_message:
Cluster model objects wrapper

Currently a model of the cluster is constructed every time a strategy is
executed, which will not scale in production or in larger environments.
If Watcher intends to be used by larger envirionments it needs a more
robust way to construct and maintain a model of the cluster. An
in-memory cache of this model can be built up and kept fresh via
notifications from services of interest in addition to periodic syncing
logic.

Co-Authored-By: Vincent FRANCOISE <Vincent.FRANCOISE@b-com.com>
Change-Id: I338b1169049c80638c5229648c6f26ed39a9b622

commit_message:
libvirt: attach configdrive after instance XML

In order to expose device tagging metadata in the configdrive, the
latter needs to be attached after the instance XML has been generated
and device addresses are known, but before the guest OS runs, as
it may depend on cloud-init data on the config drive.

This patch moves configdrive creation after the instance XML has
been generated but before the guest runs.

Partially implements: blueprint virt-device-role-tagging
Co-authored-by: Vladik Romanovsky <vromanso@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I931421ea688641e2ceb212c6dc099639c53433f2

subject: Add caching on get_test_runs_by_build_name
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2016-06-29 20:02:18.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_health/tests/test_api.py', 'openstack_health/api.py'], 'message': 'Add caching on get_test_runs_by_build_name

This commit enables simple caching on the results from the
get_test_runs_by_build_name. This API call involves one of the slowest
subunit2sql DB calls we make and is a good candidate for caching.
Right now, we just cache on name and the request datestamps which will
result in a lot of potential cache misses as people request varied
dates and/or build_names. So there is probably room for additional
optimizations in the future.

Change-Id: I7582188f4f027bc86375056e5cf60cca3a760ce8
'}]
commit_message:
Add caching on get_test_runs_by_build_name

This commit enables simple caching on the results from the
get_test_runs_by_build_name. This API call involves one of the slowest
subunit2sql DB calls we make and is a good candidate for caching.
Right now, we just cache on name and the request datestamps which will
result in a lot of potential cache misses as people request varied
dates and/or build_names. So there is probably room for additional
optimizations in the future.

Change-Id: I7582188f4f027bc86375056e5cf60cca3a760ce8

commit_message:
Concrete role assignments for federated users

"Shadow users: unified identity" implementation:
Allow concrete role assignments for federated users. Currently,
federated users get roles from mapped group assignments. However, with
the shadow users implementation, federated users are mapped to
identities in the backend; thus, can be assigned roles.

This patch returns locally assigned roles with the mapped group roles
for federated users; allowing for authorization for those roles.

bp shadow-users-newton

Change-Id: I9a150ded6c4b556627147d2671be15d6a3794ba5

Changing config parameters by one test can lead to wrong behavior
other tests in race conditions. Use a mechanism for overwriting
config options (self.flags and self.override_config methods of TestCase).

Change-Id: I4d3200dbaf3ffcd76a04caaec1b9ee166169d6f1

commit_message:
Replace mock with self.override_config

Changing config parameters by one test can lead to wrong behavior
other tests in race conditions. Use a mechanism for overwriting
config options (self.flags and self.override_config methods of TestCase).
This patch allows to use a standard approach.

Change-Id: I4d3200dbaf3ffcd76a04caaec1b9ee166169d6f1

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 5170, 'name': 'Microsoft Hyper-V CI', 'email': 'hyper-v_ci@microsoft.com', 'username': 'hyper-v-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 6873, 'name': 'Matt Riedemann', 'email': 'mriedem.os@gmail.com', 'username': 'mriedem'}, {'_account_id': 12898, 'name': 'Tony Breeds', 'email': 'tony@bakeyournoodle.com', 'username': 'tonyb'}, {'_account_id': 16376, 'name': 'Intel NFV CI', 'email': 'openstack-nfv-ci@intel.com', 'username': 'intel-nfv-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 16897, 'name': 'Virtuozzo Storage CI', 'email': 'vzstorage-ci@virtuozzo.com', 'username': 'vzstorage-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-05-25 15:06:34.000000000', 'files': ['nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_mgr.py', 'nova/network/model.py', 'nova/compute/manager.py'], 'message': "Clean up networks with SR-IOV binding on reschedule

Currently, when instace is being rescheduled due to a
failed spawn, it's allocated network port bindings are
updated with the info of rescheduled host.
However, the inforamtion about any allocated SR-IOV devices
is not being updated, nor these devices are being reallocated
on the rescheduled host.

This patch adds a method to check if networks should
be deallocated on reschedule, based on it's VNIC type.
This will be used to trigger network cleanup on
reschedule if SR-IOV VNIC type is being used in the
port binding.

(cherry picked from commit 77ab8f29ca19de7667ff32e798bdb4154a0c105e)
Change-Id: Ie327ef021c674f4d7fe95775906a46a49c1c82e7
"}]
commit_message:
Clean up networks with SR-IOV binding on reschedule

Currently, when instace is being rescheduled due to a
failed spawn, it's allocated network port bindings are
updated with the info of rescheduled host.
However, the inforamtion about any allocated SR-IOV devices
is not being updated, nor these devices are being reallocated
on the rescheduled host.

This patch adds a method to check if networks should
be deallocated on reschedule, based on it's VNIC type.
This will be used to trigger network cleanup on
reschedule if SR-IOV VNIC type is being used in the
port binding.

(cherry picked from commit 77ab8f29ca19de7667ff32e798bdb4154a0c105e)
Change-Id: Ie327ef021c674f4d7fe95775906a46a49c1c82e7

commit_message:
Make it possible to use enginefacade decorators with class methods

The decorator form can now be used with bound methods after a fix
for the related bug was merged. Mention this in docs and release
notes, so that people are aware of it.

A new test is added to make sure this also works with class methods
(as well as to check that the proposed decorator applying order
is actually correct).

Related-Bug: #1520195

Change-Id: Ifea08114d6d89de9d67fcae397eb94c0afc4d339

subject: Rename [DEFAULT] keystone.conf module to keystone.conf.default
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-06-29 19:03:52.000000000', 'files': ['keystone/conf/__init__.py', 'keystone/conf/default.py'], 'message': 'Rename [DEFAULT] keystone.conf module to keystone.conf.default

The renames the config module which default the [DEFAULT] configuration
section from 'base' (a name adopted based on nova's precedence with
nova.conf.base) to 'default', which should make it slightly easier for
developers to navigate the keystone.conf package, since all other
configuration modules directly reflect the name of the section they're
defining.

Also note, that we could take this one step further and call the module
keystone.conf.DEFAULT, but it's actually a PEP8 violation to name
module in uppercase (it reads like a reference to a constant in the
keystone.conf module). From PEP8:

    Modules should have short, all-lowercase names. Underscores can be
    used in the module name if it improves readability."

Source: https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#package-and-module-names

Change-Id: I78d4ecf67ddcb5c3c46ce0c85e1f8330fbf99877
'}]
commit_message:
Rename [DEFAULT] keystone.conf module to keystone.conf.default

The renames the config module which default the [DEFAULT] configuration
section from 'base' (a name adopted based on nova's precedence with
nova.conf.base) to 'default', which should make it slightly easier for
developers to navigate the keystone.conf package, since all other
configuration modules directly reflect the name of the section they're
defining.

Also note, that we could take this one step further and call the module
keystone.conf.DEFAULT, but it's actually a PEP8 violation to name
module in uppercase (it reads like a reference to a constant in the
keystone.conf module). From PEP8:

    Modules should have short, all-lowercase names. Underscores can be
    used in the module name if it improves readability."

Source: https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#package-and-module-names

Change-Id: I78d4ecf67ddcb5c3c46ce0c85e1f8330fbf99877

commit_message:
CI: specinfra, xenial, lint, puppet bug.

Fix beaker job for pacemaker.  When
https://tickets.puppetlabs.com/browse/BKR-851 is fixed, remove it.

The xenial node definition is now gated for Newton, add it to the mix.

Fix puppet puppet-lint-absolute_classname-check.

Work around https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppet/pull/2633 where contain
cannot have a absolute class name as parameter in puppet 3.6.

For Ubuntu Xenial we are bitten by this
https://tickets.puppetlabs.com/browse/BKR-821, where puppet is installed
in /opt/puppetlabs/bin

The package pacemaker-mgmt is not available on Ubuntu Xenial, adjust to
this.  Dbus is required by pacemaker and not installed as a dependency:
http://logs.openstack.org/36/332836/7/check/gate-puppet-pacemaker-puppet-beaker-rspec-ubuntu-xenial/5e1ad11/console.html#_2016-06-23_16_03_00_952026

Add necessary support files for reno.

Adjust the metadata.json.

Change-Id: I22e207f758b94586ebf2333668c092fff3aaebac

commit_message:
Use Openstack CLI for setting undercloud quota

With nova v2.1 API being enabled now, the undercloud TLS setup is
broken since it will try to access an uncencrypted endpoint instead of
the TLS endpoint. This is not an issue with OpenStack CLI which we
should be moving to anyway.

Change-Id: I4af9961050cd83fa3b88d70c90c76db6dbf77141
Closes-Bug: #1595423

commit_message:
Install docker for tests

We have some test cases which attempt to build docker images, therefore
we need docker.

Fix a few bugs that showed up when we run docker tests - we need to
docker rm with sudo and docker images don't always have a /tmp so check
before unmounting it.

commit_message:
Add exponential gap to retry decorator

This sets the retry interval to 100 ms and turns on the
inc_retry_interval flag which doubles the interval on each
failure to our standard retry decorator. This avoids exhausting
all of the retries in a very short window.

With our MAX_RETRIES set to 10, this means it will sleep a cumulative
time of about 8 seconds if all retry attempts fail.

Change-Id: Ife01e8e5444b035cf797e3d575c6799f92a021a5
